title: For Sale:  Weatherby Vanguard S2 .308/Nikon Buckmasters 3-9x42/case/slings/green light
postcontent: No trades, CASH only and for pick up at my home in Hyde Park only please....thanks.  Purchased new October 2016 for my dad to use during rifle season still have the Weatherby box, trigger lock and manual/paperwork.  Mission accomplished took a doe and a ton of hogs.  I already have another .308 and too many other rifles...it filled a gap for me last year. 24" barrel with 1 in 9 RH twist and wrapped from head to toe in a soft non-adhesive Mossy Oak Break Up Infinity camo(grey synthetic stock underneath).  3 position safety, fluted bolt is silky smooth and hinged floor plate(like the 700 BDL's) for ease of unloading the magazine especially in the dark.  The rifle is currently zerod at 200 yards with Hornady American Whitetail 150g .308. which means it is ~ 1 1/2" high at 100 yards.  The Nikon BDC while new to me with this glass was surprisingly accurate.  I took it out to 360 lasered from the corner of our range which just happened to coincide within 10 yards of the 2nd subtension on 9x with my load data punched into their Nikon Spot On calculator.  Closed the bolt and rocked the 4" popper leaning off the hood of my truck which is nearly 1MOA not apples to apples, but 4" at 400 is 1MOA(only able to stretch to 360 though). This rifle is ready to go hunt today and it's already been bloody out to 221 yards right through the boiler room the heart looked like burgered ground chuck it's a stone cold knock out machine for freezer meat.   - Nikon Buckmasters 3-9x42 with BDC reticle.  Bungee lens covers included, but not shown.- Talley Manufacturing lightweight one piece base/mount size medium for 1" tubes and objective lenses up to 44mm- Air Tech Slip On recoil pad(new never mounted)- Bull Dog 52" waterproof scoped rifle case - Gun Monkey backpack sling adapter with 2 Browning Excelerator Mossy Oak Break Up Infinity slings.  Fantastic for hunting and hiking, but especially for climbing a stand or using a climber.  No more tow lines and potentially banging the rifle around....it's on your back.  If you don't like the backpack setup just take off the adapter and use one of the 2 Browning Excelerators like you usually would, but you are going to love the backpack no more adjusting for a slipping rifle when hiking.  - Green light with scope mount.  These are fantastic for just b/f sun up or just after sun down you can light up game and they don't even blink.  Have taken many hogs with this setup.Nothing else to add, but feel free to ask any technical questions I'm a tech dork and enjoy talking about all things hunting/shooting.  My firearms are always cleaned the day they are fired and maintained meticulously.

title: For Sale/Trade:   1924 COLT "Transition" 1911 .45 Rare, 1 of 4999 Produced
postcontent: This a guns collectors dream come true, and is priced to sell.  If you are not familuar with colt firearms, 1924 - 1938 was known as the "Transition" period.  Colt didn't have a contract with the military to produce the 1911 yet, so they produced 10,000 blued military edition pistols, and 4,999 nickle plated ones.  They were produced in 1924, and they were known as the "transition" gun.  These sell on online auctions from 5,750 - 10,000, and this one is in amazing condition for its age.  The only modification done to this gun was done by colt where they changed out the firing pin for a stainless version.  It has the original hand grips, and while many say there were nicle plate transitions produced, do your research.  This is a very RARE gun to see up for sale, and at this price it should sell quickly.
